actions.comment:
Thanks for the question. SkiaSharp doesn't include a built-in PPM codec, but you can load PPM pixel data using the raw pixel APIs.

The approach shown in @simonegli8's comment works well — parse the PPM header, then create an `SKBitmap` with `SKColorType.Rgb888x` and `SKAlphaType.Opaque`:

```csharp
var info = new SKImageInfo(width, height, SKColorType.Rgb888x, SKAlphaType.Opaque);
var bitmap = new SKBitmap(info);
for (int y = 0; y < height; y++)
    for (int x = 0; x < width; x++)
    {
        int i = (y * width + x) * 3;
        bitmap.SetPixel(x, y, new SKColor(rgb[i], rgb[i+1], rgb[i+2]));
    }
```

For larger images, converting the 3-byte RGB data to 4-byte RGBX and using `SKBitmap.InstallPixels` avoids per-pixel overhead. Note that `Rgb888x` uses 4 bytes per pixel (RGB + padding), so the raw 3-byte PPM data must be expanded before use with bulk APIs.
